he repelling force between molecules. Part II covers van der Waals' theory, the principles of general mechanics needed for a gas theory, gases with compound molecules, derivation of van der Waals' equation by means of the virial concept, theory of dissociation and supplements to the laws of thermal equilibrium in gases with compound molecules. Combining rigorous mathematical analysis with pragmatic treatment of physical and chemical applications, Lectures on Gas Theory was the standard work on kinetic theory in the first quarter of the 20th century. It remains "one of the greatest books in the history of exact sciences." ; Mark Kac.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aKinetic theory of gases. 4acalorimetry. 4akinetic theory. 4aphysics. 4athermodynamics. 7aSCIENCE / Mechanics / Thermodynamics.2bisacsh1 aBrush, Stephen G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052032746740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520327474?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520327474423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520327474/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles